  <h1>Transfer pricing in India: a practical guide</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>7 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>Transfer pricing in India, governed by Sections 92 to 92F of the Income-tax Act, requires that international transactions between associated enterprises be priced at arm's length.</b> Taxpayers must maintain prescribed documentation, obtain an accountant's report in Form 3CEB, and face transfer-pricing adjustments and penalties for non-compliance.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">The building blocks</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">The compliance chain</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">Adjustments and the penalty regime</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Managing TP risk</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">The building blocks</h2>
<ul><li><b>Associated enterprises (Section 92A)</b> &mdash; enterprises linked by management, control or capital (e.g. 26% voting power, dependence on borrowings, IP or sales).</li><li><b>International transaction (Section 92B)</b> &mdash; a cross-border transaction between AEs in goods, services, intangibles, finance or cost-sharing.</li><li><b>Arm's length price (Section 92C)</b> &mdash; the price that would apply between unrelated parties.</li><li><b>Specified domestic transactions (Section 92BA)</b> &mdash; certain domestic related-party dealings above a threshold.</li></ul>

  <h2 id="s1">The compliance chain</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Requirement</th><th>Provision / form</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Maintain TP documentation</td><td>Section 92D, Rule 10D</td></tr><tr><td>Accountant's report</td><td>Form 3CEB, Section 92E (by 31 October)</td></tr><tr><td>Master File</td><td>Form 3CEAA (above thresholds)</td></tr><tr><td>Country-by-Country Report</td><td>Form 3CEAD, Section 286 (large MNE groups)</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

  <h2 id="s2">Adjustments and the penalty regime</h2>
<p>If the price is not at arm's length, the Transfer Pricing Officer makes an <b>adjustment</b> increasing taxable income, and a <b>secondary adjustment</b> under Section 92CE may deem the excess as an advance attracting notional interest. Penalties include 2% of the transaction value for documentation/3CEB failures, and under-reporting penalties on the adjustment.</p>

  <h2 id="s3">Managing TP risk</h2>
<ul><li>Use <b>Advance Pricing Agreements (APA)</b> for certainty on method and margin.</li><li>Consider <b>safe harbour</b> rules for eligible transactions.</li><li>Keep contemporaneous documentation and a robust benchmarking study.</li><li>Align TP with <a href="permanent-establishment-dtaa-india.html">PE</a> and <a href="income-tax-foreign-income-dtaa-fema.html">DTAA</a> positions.</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is transfer pricing?</summary><p>A set of rules requiring that transactions between associated enterprises (typically cross-border group companies) be priced as if between unrelated parties &mdash; the arm's length principle &mdash; under Sections 92 to 92F.</p></details>
    <details><summary>When is Form 3CEB required?</summary><p>Where a taxpayer has entered into an international transaction or a specified domestic transaction with an associated enterprise; the accountant's report in Form 3CEB is due by 31 October.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What is an APA?</summary><p>An Advance Pricing Agreement between a taxpayer and the tax authority that fixes the transfer-pricing method and arm's length margin for future years, giving certainty and reducing litigation.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>Sections 92-92F require arm's length pricing between AEs.</li><li>Documentation (Rule 10D) + Form 3CEB by 31 October are mandatory.</li><li>Master File and CbCR apply to large MNE groups.</li><li>APA and safe harbour reduce TP uncertainty.</li></ul>
  </div>

